1.body: Vex supports Linux, macOS and Windows. Assuming that cargo is installed, open a terminal and run the following— cargo install --git https://github.com/TheSignPainter98/vex Test the installation by running vex. If vex appears unavailable, ensure that ~/.cargo/bin/ is present in your $PATH and then retry.
1.title: Installation

10.body:

git commit -m 'Added vexes'

11.body: This guide provides two solutions. If only one matching child is needed, use the first. If all matching children is needed, use the second.
11.breadcrumbs: How-to guides » How to search child nodes » How to search child nodes
11.title: How to search child nodes

12.body:
Put the cursor at the end of vex script. If absent, copy the following function into the script— def find_child(node, predicate): for child in node.children(): if predicate(child): return child match = find_child(child, predicate) if match != None: return match return None Move to where the matching child is required. Call the find_child function, passing the node whose children are to be searched and a function or lambda which takes a node returns whether it is the desired one. For example, to find the first child let_declaration node, use the following— find_child( node_to_search, lambda node: node.kind == 'let_declaration',
)
12.breadcrumbs: How-to guides » How to search child nodes » How to search child nodes, returning the first match
12.title: How to search child nodes, returning the first match

13.body:
Put the cursor at the end of vex script. If absent, copy the following function into the script— def find_all_children(node, predicate, allow_nested=False): def _find_children(node, predicate, allow_nested, ret) for child in node.children(): if predicate(child): ret.append(child) if not allow_nested: continue _find_children(child, predicate, allow_nested=allow_nested, ret=ret) ret = [] _find_children(node, predicate, allow_nested, ret) return ret Move to where the matching child is required. Call the find_all_children function, passing the node whose children are to be searched and a function or lambda which takes a node returns whether to include it in the output. For example, to find all child let_declaration nodes, use the following— find_all_children( node_to_search, lambda node: node.kind == 'let_declaration', allow_nested=True,
)
13.breadcrumbs: How-to guides » How to search child nodes » How to search child nodes, returning all matches
13.title: How to search child nodes, returning all matches

14.body: This guide provides two solutions. If only one matching parent is needed, use the first. If all matching parents is needed, use the second.

14.title: How to search parent nodes

15.body:
Put the cursor at the end of vex script. If absent, copy the following function into the script— def find_parent(node, predicate): for parent in node.parents(): if predicate(parent): return parent return None Move to where the matching child is required. Call the find_parent function, passing the node whose parents are to be searched and a function or lambda which takes a node returns whether it is the desired one. For example, to find the first parent let_declaration node, use the following— find_parent( node_to_search, lambda node: node.kind == 'let_declaration',
)
15.breadcrumbs: How-to guides » How to search parent nodes » How to search parent nodes, returning the first match
15.title: How to search parent nodes, returning the first match

16.body:
Put the cursor at the end of vex script. If absent, copy the following function into the script— def find_all_parents(node, predicate, allow_nested=False): return [ parent for parent in node.parents() if predicate(parent) ] Move to where the matching child is required. Call the find_all_parents function, passing the node whose parents are to be searched and a function or lambda which takes a node returns whether to include it in the output. For example, to find all parent let_declaration nodes, use the following— find_all_parents( node_to_search, lambda node: node.kind == 'let_declaration',
) The variable let_declarations is now a list.

18.body: Globs are patterns, commonly seen in shell language, used to represent one or multiple file paths. Vex supports the following glob features: [1] ? matches any single character. * matches any (possibly empty) sequence of characters. ** matches the current directory and arbitrary subdirectories. This sequence must form a single path component, so both **a and b** are invalid and will result in an error. A sequence of more than two consecutive * characters is also invalid. [...] matches any character inside the brackets. Character sequences can also specify ranges of characters, as ordered by Unicode, so e.g. [0-9] specifies any character between 0 and 9 inclusive. An unclosed bracket is invalid. [!...] is the negation of [...], i.e. it matches any characters not in the brackets. The metacharacters ?, *, [, ] can be matched by using brackets (e.g. [?]). When a ] occurs immediately following [ or [! then it is interpreted as being part of, rather then ending, the character set, so ] and NOT ] can be matched by []] and [!]] respectively. The - character can be specified inside a character sequence pattern by placing it at the start or the end, e.g. [abc-]. This list originally came from the Pattern docs in the excellent glob Rust crate , used by this project.
18.title: Globs

4.body: Open a terminal, type and run— vex list languages Find the name of the desired language in the list. Open vex.toml. If absent, on a new line at the end of the file, type out a new section [<language-name>]. In this section, if absent, type out a new use-for = [] field. In the square brackets from the previous step, type a glob in double-quotes which matches the desired file.

5.body: Open a terminal in the root directory of your project. Type and run— vex init You should now see a new file, vex.toml, and a new directory, vexes/ containing an example vex.

6.body: In terminal, copy the vex ID to ignore (warning[<vex-id-here>]). Open the file containing the code which triggered the warning. Move the cursor to the start of that code. Type out a comment with the following text— vex:ignore <vex-id-here>

8.body: Open the file containing the init function which sets up the vex. If the open_project event is observed, put the cursor at the top of its event handler function and type the following— if vex.lenient: return If the open_file event is observed, do the same to its event handler function.
